	"notes": [
		{
			"id": "nITrGXD2MhPm-W48k",
			"markdown": "The Pilot is the master of vehicles, navigation, and dangerous movement. Whether flying a battered freighter through hostile space, threading a grav-bike through neon traffic, commanding a tank platoon, or driving a convoy across desolate wastelands, you get people where they need to go and bring them back alive. In many campaigns, the Pilot is also the scout, courier, explorer, or transport specialist. You excel in motion, pursuit, terrain, and situational awareness, and your skills often determine whether the group escapes disaster or dies in it.\n\nYour core competency is either Piloting or Driving, depending on the setting and vehicle type, but a good Pilot is far more than someone who can steer a machine. Many Pilots also serve as navigators, scouts, gunners, mechanics, couriers, expedition leaders, smugglers, or vehicle commanders, developing expertise in Navigation, Mechanic, Gunner, Electronics Operation, Leadership, Strategy, or Survival. Even away from the controls, you remain useful by planning routes, spotting danger, coordinating crews, maintaining vehicles, handling logistics, or guiding the party through hostile environments. Whether you are a disciplined military professional, a hardened convoy driver, a daring explorer, or a thrill-seeking rogue surviving on nerve and instinct, the group depends on you whenever the journey itself becomes dangerous.\n\nThe *Ace Pilot* lives for speed, precision, and impossible maneuvers. Fighter aces, interceptor jockeys, stunt pilots, smugglers, racers, and elite insertion specialists all fit this archetype. Ace Pilots thrive in high-speed pursuits, dogfights, evasive flying, and dangerous extractions where reflexes matter more than caution. They emphasize Piloting, Navigation, Gunner, Electronics Operation (Sensors), Hot Pilot, Enhanced Dodge (Vehicular), Combat Reflexes, Fearlessness, Daredevil, Luck, and Perfect Balance. Common disadvantages include Overconfidence, On the Edge, Lecherousness, Bad Temper, Trickster, Compulsive Carousing, or Greed.\n\nThe *Rigger* is a hands-on vehicle specialist who keeps machines operating under impossible conditions. Tank crews, mecha jockeys, rover operators, scavenger pilots, bush flyers, convoy drivers, and space truckers belong to this archetype. Riggers excel at maintenance, improvisation, field repairs, and coaxing broken vehicles through hostile terrain long after they should have failed. They focus on Driving or Piloting, Mechanic, Freight Handling, Gunner, Electronics Repair, Scrounging, High Manual Dexterity, Combat Reflexes, Danger Sense, Fit, Gizmo, and Single-Minded. Typical disadvantages include Workaholic, Miserliness, Stubbornness, Compulsive Gambling, Alcoholism, Obsession, or Code of Honor (Professional).\n\nThe *Captain* combines vehicle expertise with leadership, logistics, and command presence. Naval officers, expedition chiefs, convoy commanders, smugglers, merchant captains, pirate lords, submarine commanders, and transport bosses all fit this archetype. Captains thrive when coordinating crews, maintaining discipline, planning long voyages, and keeping people functioning under pressure and isolation. They emphasize Shiphandling, Leadership, Strategy, Navigation, Electronics Operation (Communications), Crewman skills, Intuitive Admiral, Charisma, Cultural Adaptability, Born Spacer, Luck, and Unfazeable. Common disadvantages include Sense of Duty, Code of Honor (Soldier’s, Pirate’s, or Professional), Overconfidence, Fanaticism, Honesty, Workaholic, or Selfish.\n\nThe *Scout* specializes in exploration, reconnaissance, and survival beyond the edge of civilization. Recon pilots, pathfinders, search-and-rescue crews, wilderness couriers, and deep-space explorers belong to this archetype. Scouts thrive in unknown territory where maps fail, infrastructure disappears, and a single mistake can strand the group forever. They focus on Navigation, Observation, Survival, Astronomy, Geology, Free Fall, Piloting or Driving, Danger Sense, Absolute Direction, Intuition, Fearlessness, Night Vision, and Fit. Common disadvantages include Curious, Loner, Xenophilia, Xenophobia, Nightmares, Sense of Duty, or Stubbornness.\n\nMany Pilots branch into secondary specialties depending on the campaign. Some become mechanics, smugglers, explorers, or tacticians, while others develop expertise in logistics, military command, scouting, or dangerous stunt work. In many adventures, the Pilot determines not only how the group travels, but whether they can escape pursuit, survive hostile environments, or reach the destination at all."
		}
	]
}
